owl:Ontology.dc:description: “Municipal by-laws are public regulatory laws which apply in a certain area. The main difference between a by-law and a law passed by a national/federal or regional/state body is that a by-law is made by a non-sovereign body, which derives its authority from another governing body, and can only be made on a limited range of matters. A local council or municipal government derives its power to pass laws through a law of the national or regional government which specifies what things the town or city may regulate through by-laws. It is therefore a form of delegated legislation.” (Wikipedia, 2020) “A municipal by-law is no different than any other law of the land, and can be enforced with penalties, challenged in court and must comply with higher levels of law. Municipal bylaws are often enforceable through the public justice system, and offenders can be charged with a criminal offence for breach of a bylaw.” (Alberta, 2017) The intent of the Bylaw ontology is to capture the major components of a city bylaw, such as dates, geographic areas of application, penalties, etc. It is not intended to provide a legal semantics with which to codify a particular bylaw. The following three types of bylaws are represented in the Bylaw Ontology (Alberta, 2017): 1. Main bylaws; 2. Amending bylaws, which reflect material changes, in principle or substance, to an existing bylaw; and 3. Revision bylaws, which reflect limited changes to an existing bylaw.

owl:Class.dc:description: A Parcel is a way of defining some area in an urban system. A Parcel has a Location. A Parcel may be classified as having some type of Land Use. There may be other types (subclasses) of Parcel, defined in more precise or different ways, such as a Zone.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Agriculture and Agri-Foods Canada Classification is a type (subclass of) land use classification. The codes are based on the IPCC (International Panel on Climate Change) protocol.
Annual and perennial TBD: Should this be the same as the CLUMPCropland class?
Natural and human-made. TBD: should this be the same as the CLUMPWater class?

owl:Class.dc:description: A - Cropland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'A' Cropland - Land used for annual field crops such as grain, oilseeds, sugar beets, tobacco, potatoes, field vegetables and canning crops. Associated fallow, and land being cleared for field crops are also included.

owl:Class.dc:description: Z - Water areas
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'Z' Additional code added during data integration for water areas based on the CLI shoreline maps.
The population of employed residents in a given area (Parcel)
Treed areas >1 ha in size
Wetland with forest cover
Natural grass and shrubs used for cattle grazing
Natural grass and shrubs with no apparent use (forest openings, alpine meadows, tundra, etc.)

owl:Class.dc:description: H - Horticulture
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'H' Horticulture, poultry and fur operations. Land used for intensive cultivation of vegetables and small fruits, includes market gardens, nurseries, flower and bulb farms and sod farms. Large scale commercial fur and poultry farms are also included because of their specialized agricultural nature.

owl:Class.dc:description: P - Improved pasture and forage crops
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'P' Improved pasture and forage crops.- Land used for improved pasture or for the production of hay and other cultivated fodder crops, including land being cleared for these purposes.

The LBCS recognizes different dimensions of Land Use: Activity, Function, Structure, Site, and Ownership Classifications. Each dimension is further defined by a taxonomy of specialized classifications. For each dimension, we introduce an equivalent class name for disambiguation, e.g. to distinguish between the Activity dimension of land use (we refer to this as ActivityClassification) and the notion of an Activity in icity.

Land Use Classifications provide a means of describing the land cover/use in a standard way. Various classification systems are used to identify types of land use. Currently, we include LBCS, CLUMP, and AAFC.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify all classes defined in the Land Use ontology.

owl:Class.dc:description: E - Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'E' Mines, quarries, sand and gravel pits, open excavations. Land used in the past or present for the extraction of earth materials.

owl:Class.dc:description: U - Non-productive woodland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'U' Non-productive woodland. Land covered by scrub growth.

owl:Class.dc:description: G - Orchards and vineyards
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'G' Orchards and vineyards. Land used for the production of tree fruits, hops and grapes.
Rock, beaches, ice, barren land

owl:Class.dc:description: O - Outdoor recreation
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'O' Outdoor recreation - Land used for private or public outdoor recreational purposes. Some examples are: golf courses, parks, beaches, summer cottage areas, game preserves and historic sites.

owl:Class.dc:description: T - Productive woodland
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'T' Productive woodland.Wooded land with trees having over 25% canopy cover and being over 20 feet in height approximately. Artificially restocked areas, or plantations are included regardless of age. Much cut-over and burned-over land is included.
The population that resides within a given area (Parcel)
Primary, secondary and tertiary
Built-up and urban

owl:Class.dc:description: M - Swamp, marsh or bog
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'M' Swamp, marsh, or bog. Open wetlands except those which frequently dry up or show evidence of grazing or hay cutting.
Wetland with tree cover
Treed areas <1 ha in size
Areas not classified due to clouds.

owl:Class.dc:description: K - Unimproved pasture and range land
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'K' Rough grazing and range land. Areas of natural grasslands, sedges, herbaceous plants and abandoned farmland whether used for grazing or not. Bushes and trees may cover up to 25% of the area. Intermittently wet hay lands (sloughs or meadows) are included as long as the land is utilized. Within some grassy, open woodlands, bushes and trees may exceed 25% cover if the area is actively grazed and no other use dominates.

owl:Class.dc:description: 8 - Unmapped areas
L - Unproductive land - rock
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'L' Rock and other unvegetated surfaces - rock barrens, badlands, alkaline flats, gravel bars, eroded river banks, mine dumps. Unproductive land which does not support vegetation.

owl:Class.dc:description: S - Unproductive land - sand
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'S' Sand, sand bars, sand flats, dunes and beaches - Unproductive unconsolidated land which does not support vegetation.

owl:Class.dc:description: B - Urban built-up area
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'B' Built-up area. Land occupied by cities, towns, and villages, or by isolated units away from settlements such as manufacturing plants, rail yards, and military camps. Parks and other open spaces within built-up areas are also included.
Undifferentiated wetland
Wetland with grass cover
Wetland with shrub cover

owl:Class.dc:description: Business Establishment: A Business establishment is a physical location where a Firm conducts business. A Business Establishment has a Location and may have an address.

Employee: An Firm has some Employees, whom it employs for some Occupation. An Employee is a type of Organization Agent. An Employee may be employed at a particular Business Establishment. An Employee may be responsible for one or more Roles within the Organization. An Employee is employed by some Organization, unless the Person is self-employed. An Employee has a Wage/Salary and may work at some Location (this may be the location of the Firm, an alternate Location, or a Location that is subject to change).
Firm: A Firm is a type of organization. A Firm has an address and an industry type, and some Employees. A Firm may have a Business Establishment(s).

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: General Office / Clerical

owl:Class.dc:description: A goal represents some state or complex states, and allows for the representation of various groups' responsibilities.
Occupation: An Occupation is performed by some Person. An Occupation has a type (e.g. sales, skilled trades)
Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the iCity-Organization ontology.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Professional / Management / Technical

owl:Class.dc:description: Role: A Role has a single (possibly complex) Goal. A Role has some authority, requires some skill, and may also have some associated processes.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Retail Sales and Service
Manufacturing / Construction / Trades

owl:Class.dc:description: A Person may have a unique identifier. A Person has a date of birth, and may have a date of death. A Person may be a member of a Family and/or a Household. A Person has a mother and father, and may have a spouse and/or child(ren). Note that we define the parent relation as the legal relation as opposed to biological. This property may be specialized and restricted, for example hasBiologicalMother: exactly 1 Person. A Person may have some Job and associated Income. A Person may have access to some Vehicle. A Person may have access to some Bicycle. A Person may have some TransitPass. A Person has an address of residence and may have other contact information such as E-mail, phone number, etcetera. A Person has a Schedule for a given point (period) in time. Note that some properties are not defined in the Person ontology, but in an extension of the Person ontology that captures the interaction between iCity domain ontologies (e.g. Persons and their Vehicles)
Added for organizational purposes, to identify classes defined in the Person ontology.
A Qualification captures some official degree of accomplishment. It may be required for something and/or possessed by some Person.

A Skill captures an ability to perfom some activity or set of activities.

owl:Class.dc:description: Organization Agent: Members of an organization. Organization Agents have goals, authority, and may be members of some team. An Organization Agent plays a Role within the Organization.
